\begin_body

\begin_layout Chapter
RFID Anti-collision Protocols 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
This chapter presents the most common anti-collisions algorithms for passive
 RFID systems, either by using the PHY layer or the MAC layer.
 It will emphasize the anti-collision algorithms which are compatible with
 the EPCglobal C1 G2 standard, as it is the main focus of this thesis, because
 it is the most suitable standard for the dense passive RFID applications.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
This chapter is organized as follows: Section 1 gives an overview about
 the PHY layer anti-collision algorithms.
 In section 2, different MAC-layer anti-collision algorithms are presented.
 Afterwards, a brief description for the EPCglobal C1 G2 reading process
 will be presented in section 3.
 Section 4 will give an introduction about the main PHY-layer parameters,
 e.g.
 the collision recovery and the slots duration in modern RFID readers.
 Then, it will show the effect of these parameters on the MAC-layer anti-collisi
on algorithm, which will be the main focus of the remaining part in this
 thesis.
 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Section
PHY-Layer Anti-collision Protocols
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Different PHY layer anti-collision protocols have been developed to separate
 colliding tag signals on the PHY layer.
 Figure 
\begin_inset CommandInset ref
LatexCommand ref
reference "fig:Existing-PHY-Layer-anti-collisio"

\end_inset

 shows the most common PHY layer anti-collision protocols, which are: FDMA,
 SDMA, CDMA and TDMA.
 These algorithms will be briefly discussed in the following paragraphs:
\end_layout

\begin_layout Paragraph
Frequency Division Multiple Access (FDMA):
\begin_inset CommandInset nomenclature
LatexCommand nomenclature
symbol "FDMA"
description "Frequency Division Multiple Access"

\end_inset

 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
In this protocol, the frequency band is divided into different sub-frequency
 bands and tags are distributed among them.
 However, this technique adds complexity to the system.
 Readers should be able to decode different frequencies at the same time.
 Moreover, tags should be able to select its desirable sub-channel, which
 is incompatible with EPCglobal C1 G2.
 Only active tags can do such function 
\begin_inset CommandInset citation
LatexCommand cite
key "FDMA"

\end_inset

.
\begin_inset Float figure
wide false
sideways false
status collapsed

\begin_layout Plain Layout
\align center
\begin_inset Graphics
	filename PHY_anti_collision.emf
	lyxscale 15
	width 55page%

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Plain Layout
\begin_inset Caption Standard

\begin_layout Plain Layout
Common existing PHY-Layer anti-collision protocols 
\begin_inset CommandInset label
LatexCommand label
name "fig:Existing-PHY-Layer-anti-collisio"

\end_inset

 
\end_layout

\end_inset


\end_layout

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Paragraph*
Space Division Multiple Access (SDMA):
\begin_inset CommandInset nomenclature
LatexCommand nomenclature
symbol "SDMA"
description "Space Division Multiple Access"

\end_inset

 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
This technique makes use of spreading tags over the reading area.
 It provides a high increase in the reading efficiency 
\begin_inset CommandInset citation
LatexCommand cite
key "SDMA"

\end_inset

.
 The main drawback is the cost of implementing the RFID reader with multiple
 antennas.
 Moreover, in dense applications, the distances between the tags are very
 small in order to be distributed on the reading area.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Paragraph*
Code Division Multiple Access (CDMA):
\begin_inset CommandInset nomenclature
LatexCommand nomenclature
symbol "CDMA"
description "Code Division Multiple Access"

\end_inset

 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
This protocol uses spread-spectrum modulation techniques to transmit the
 data over the entire spectrum
\begin_inset CommandInset citation
LatexCommand cite
key "CDMA"

\end_inset

.
 CDMA is the ideal procedure for many applications, e.g.
 navigation systems.
 However, the cost of the tags will severely increase.
 Thereby, it is not an optimum protocol for dense RFID applications.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Paragraph*
Time Division Multiple Access (TDMA):
\begin_inset CommandInset nomenclature
LatexCommand nomenclature
symbol "TDMA"
description "Time Division Multiple Access"

\end_inset

 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
In this protocol, a single frequency band is divided into time slots and
 assigned to the tags.
 In this technique, each tag must be synchronized to the time slots and
 sends its information at the beginning of the selected slot 
\begin_inset CommandInset citation
LatexCommand cite
key "TDMA"

\end_inset

.
 This technique can be directly applied to passive RFID systems.
 In such systems, the simplicity of tags transfers the complexity to the
 readers, where the reader has to control the time synchronization.
 However, in active RFID systems, synchronization can be either centralized
 or distributed to the tags.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Section
MAC-Layer Anti-collision Protocols
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
PHY anti-collision proposals are not cost effective for the market challenges
 of the passive RFID technologies, because they require additional modifications
 of the tags.
 Therefore, tags collisions solutions are commonly implemented at the MAC-layer.
 This section will discuss the most common MAC-layer anti-collision protocols.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Figure 
\begin_inset CommandInset ref
LatexCommand ref
reference "fig:Common-existing-MAC-Layer"

\end_inset

 presents the main classification of the most common MAC-layer anti-collision
 protocols.
 MAC-layer anti-collision protocols are classified into two main categories:
 Deterministic protocols and probabilistic protocols.
 Deterministic or 
\begin_inset Quotes eld
\end_inset

Tree-based
\begin_inset Quotes erd
\end_inset

 protocols are used in systems with known number of tags to be identified
 in the reading area, because these protocols identify the depth of the
 tree by knowing the number of tags.
 Probabilistic or 
\begin_inset Quotes eld
\end_inset

ALOHA-based
\begin_inset Quotes erd
\end_inset

 protocols are used in systems with an unknown number of tags.
 
\begin_inset Float figure
wide false
sideways false
status collapsed

\begin_layout Plain Layout
\align center
\begin_inset Graphics
	filename MAC_anti_collision.emf
	lyxscale 15
	width 50page%

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Plain Layout
\begin_inset Caption Standard

\begin_layout Plain Layout
Common existing MAC-Layer anti-collision protocols 
\begin_inset CommandInset label
LatexCommand label
name "fig:Common-existing-MAC-Layer"

\end_inset


\end_layout

\end_inset


\end_layout

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
The following sections will discuss in details the most commonly used anti-colli
sion algorithms either deterministic or probabilistic based algorithm.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Subsection
Deterministic Anti-collision Protocols
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
These protocols are commonly named tree-based anti-collision protocols.
 Using these algorithms, the reader aims to identify a set of tags in the
 coverage area in subsequent time slots 
\begin_inset CommandInset citation
LatexCommand cite
key "Tree1"

\end_inset

.
 Each time slot contains a 
\begin_inset Quotes eld
\end_inset

Query
\begin_inset Quotes erd
\end_inset

 command, transmitted from the reader, and the response of tags in the reading
 area.
 If there is more than a single tag reply in one slot, a collision occurs
 and the reader tries to split the tags into two subgroups.
 The reader repeats the splitting procedure until it receives a single tag
 reply.
 Tree-based anti-collision protocols can be classified into two groups:
\end_layout

\begin_layout Subsubsection*
Binary Tree
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
The binary tree algorithm 
\begin_inset CommandInset citation
LatexCommand cite
key "Binary_tree_new"

\end_inset

 is commonly used in tree-based anti-collision protocols.
 Using this algorithm, if a collision occurs in a time slot, each collided
 tag selects randomly '0' or '1'.
 Thus, the colliding tags will be separated into two subgroups.
 Tags, which selected '0', always transmit their IDs to the reader first.
 If a collision occurs again, collided tags are splitted again by selecting
 '0' or '1'.
 Tags, which have selected '1', have to wait until all other tags which
 have selected '0' are successfully identified by the reader.
 This procedure continues recursively until the subset is reduced to one
 tag, that is identified without collisions.
 
\begin_inset Float figure
wide false
sideways false
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout
\align center
\begin_inset Graphics
	filename Binary_tree.emf
	lyxscale 20
	width 51page%

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Plain Layout
\begin_inset Caption Standard

\begin_layout Plain Layout
Binary tree anti-collision algorithm example 
\begin_inset CommandInset label
LatexCommand label
name "fig:Binary-tree-anti-collision"

\end_inset


\end_layout

\end_inset


\end_layout

\end_inset

 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Figure 
\begin_inset CommandInset ref
LatexCommand ref
reference "fig:Binary-tree-anti-collision"

\end_inset

 shows an example of the binary tree algorithm resolving the collision of
 four tags in a reading area.
 Thus, there is a collided time slot at the beginning.
 At time slot 
\begin_inset Formula $2$
\end_inset

, each collided tag has to choose '0' or '1' randomly.
 In the shown example, tags 
\begin_inset Formula $1$
\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset Formula $2$
\end_inset

 have selected '0'.
 However, tags 
\begin_inset Formula $3$
\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset Formula $4$
\end_inset

 have selected '1'.
 According to the binary tree algorithm, tags 
\begin_inset Formula $3$
\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset Formula $4$
\end_inset

 have to wait until tags 
\begin_inset Formula $1$
\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset Formula $2$
\end_inset

 are successfully identified.
 Therefore, time slot 
\begin_inset Formula $2$
\end_inset

 is a collided slot due to the collision between tags 
\begin_inset Formula $1$
\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset Formula $2$
\end_inset

.
 Due to this collision, both tags 
\begin_inset Formula $1$
\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset Formula $2$
\end_inset

 have to choose either '0' or '1'.
 In this example, both tags 
\begin_inset Formula $1$
\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset Formula $2$
\end_inset

 have selected '1'.
 This resulted in an empty slot in time slot 
\begin_inset Formula $3$
\end_inset

 and a collided slot in time slot 
\begin_inset Formula $4$
\end_inset

.
 Afterwards, tag 
\begin_inset Formula $1$
\end_inset

 has selected '0' and tag 
\begin_inset Formula $2$
\end_inset

 has selected '1'.
 This random selection made them separated into two successive successful
 slots (
\begin_inset Formula $5$
\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset Formula $6$
\end_inset

).
 At this moment, tags 
\begin_inset Formula $3$
\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset Formula $4$
\end_inset

 started their identification process.
 The reader repeats the previous process until identifying all tags in the
 reading area.
\begin_inset Float figure
wide false
sideways false
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout
\align center
\begin_inset Graphics
	filename Query_tree.emf
	lyxscale 20
	width 45page%

\end_inset


\end_layout

