\begin_layout Subsubsection*
Query Tree
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Another tree algorithm category is the query tree algorithm 
\begin_inset CommandInset citation
LatexCommand cite
key "Query_tree"

\end_inset

.
 It is also commonly used in tree-based anti-collision algorithms.
 Using this algorithm, the broadcast is a query signal asking the tags for
 a reply.
 If there is a collision, it starts splitting the collided tags into two
 groups by sending a new query signal with a single bit 0 or 1 randomly.
 Tags in the reading area receive this signal and match this bit with their
 ID.
 If this bit matches their ID, they transmit their ID.
 If a collision took place again, the reader adds another random bit 0 or
 1 to its next query signal.
 This process is repeated until the reader receives a successful single
 tag reply.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Figure 
\begin_inset CommandInset ref
LatexCommand ref
reference "fig:Query-tree-anti-collision"

\end_inset

 presents an example for the query tree algorithm resolving the collision
 of 4 tags in a reading area.
 At time slot 1, the reader broadcasts a query signal asking them for a
 reply.
 A collision between the four tags is taking place.
 The reader sends a '0' in a new query signal at time slot 2.
 However, there are three tags sharing this bit, so a new collision between
 the three tags is happening.
 Thereby, the reader has sent a '00' in its next query signal in time slot
 3.
 At this time, there is a collision between two tags, leading the reader
 to send '000' in time slot 4.
 At last, the reader has received a single successful reply from tag 1.
 This process is repeated until the reader identify all the tags in the
 reading area.
\begin_inset Float figure
wide false
sideways false
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout
\align center
\begin_inset Graphics
	filename ALOHA.emf
	lyxscale 20
	width 53page%

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Plain Layout
\begin_inset Caption Standard

\begin_layout Plain Layout
Example of pure ALOHA protocol 
\begin_inset CommandInset label
LatexCommand label
name "fig:Example-for-pure"

\end_inset


\end_layout

\end_inset


\end_layout

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Subsection
Probabilistic Anti-collision Protocols
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
The main disadvantage of using tree-based protocols is that these protocols
 are not efficient in dense networks (large number of tags), due to the
 increase in identification time 
\begin_inset CommandInset citation
LatexCommand cite
key "Aloha1"

\end_inset

.
 Therefore, in dense networks, ALOHA-based anti-collision protocols are
 more suitable 
\begin_inset CommandInset citation
LatexCommand cite
key "Aloha1"

\end_inset

.
 ALOHA anti-collision protocols are therefore the most commonly used in
 UHF active and passive RFID.
 ALOHA anti-collision protocols can be classified into the following four
 groups: 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Subsubsection*
Basic ALOHA
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
The first group is widely known as basic ALOHA 
\begin_inset CommandInset citation
LatexCommand cite
key "Pure_ALOHA"

\end_inset

 anti-collision protocol.
 Basic ALOHA is the simplest anti-collision protocol for passive read-only-memor
y RFID tags.
 This protocol works as follows: The reader sends a query signal to power
 the tags.
 Then, tags send their ID randomly in time.
 The reader can only recognize the single tag reply case, without any ability
 to handle the collision.
 When every tag replies to the reader without checking whether the channel
 is free or not there is always the possibility of the collision.
 In case of collision, the collided tags wait for a random duration of time
 and transmit again till it transmits successfully.
 According to 
\begin_inset CommandInset citation
LatexCommand cite
key "Pure_ALOHA"

\end_inset

, the maximum available reading efficiency is 
\begin_inset Formula $\unit[18.4]{\%}$
\end_inset

.
 Figure 
\begin_inset CommandInset ref
LatexCommand ref
reference "fig:Example-for-pure"

\end_inset

 shows an example of basic ALOHA for a single reader identifying four tags.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Subsubsection*
Slotted ALOHA
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
The second ALOHA anti-collision protocol is the slotted ALOHA (SA) 
\begin_inset CommandInset nomenclature
LatexCommand nomenclature
symbol "SA"
description "Slotted ALOHA"

\end_inset

 protocol 
\begin_inset CommandInset citation
LatexCommand cite
key "Slotted_ALOHA"

\end_inset

.
 As shown in figure 
\begin_inset CommandInset ref
LatexCommand ref
reference "fig:Example-for-slotted"

\end_inset

, slotted ALOHA is based on basic ALOHA.
 However, the time is divided into slots.
 In this protocol, the reader broadcasts a query signal which includes the
 beginning of each slot.
 Each tag chooses randomly if it will transmit in this slot or wait for
 a coming slot.
 Each tag is allowed only to start transmission at the beginning of each
 time slot.
 Therefore, the maximum possible collided time is a single complete slot.
 However, in the basic ALOHA protocol, the possible collided time is two
 slots.
 Thus, the maximum available reading efficiency using slotted ALOHA is 
\begin_inset Formula $\unit[36.8]{\%}$
\end_inset

 
\begin_inset CommandInset citation
LatexCommand cite
key "Slotted_ALOHA"

\end_inset

.
\begin_inset Float figure
wide false
sideways false
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout
\align center
\begin_inset Graphics
	filename Slotted ALOHA.emf
	lyxscale 13
	width 45page%

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Plain Layout
\begin_inset Caption Standard

\begin_layout Plain Layout
Example of slotted ALOHA 
\begin_inset CommandInset label
LatexCommand label
name "fig:Example-for-slotted"

\end_inset


\end_layout

\end_inset


\end_layout

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Subsubsection*
Framed Slotted ALOHA (FSA)
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
The third group is Framed Slotted ALOHA (FSA)
\begin_inset CommandInset nomenclature
LatexCommand nomenclature
symbol "FSA"
description "Framed Slotted ALOHA"

\end_inset

 
\begin_inset CommandInset citation
LatexCommand cite
key "Aloha1"

\end_inset

.
 The FSA anti-collision protocol uses a fixed frame length.
 Thus, the frame length is fixed during the complete tag identification
 process.
 At the beginning of each frame, the reader broadcasts a query signal to
 all  tags.
 This signal includes the frame size.
 Each tag has to choose a random number between 
\begin_inset Formula $0$
\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset Formula $L-1$
\end_inset

, where 
\begin_inset Formula $L$
\end_inset

 is the frame length.
 If a collision happens, the colliding tags have to retry in the next frame.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Figure 
\begin_inset CommandInset ref
LatexCommand ref
reference "fig:Example-for-frame"

\end_inset

 presents an example for the identification process of four tags using FSA.
 In this example, the frame length is selected to four slots.
 According to figure 
\begin_inset CommandInset ref
LatexCommand ref
reference "fig:Example-for-frame"

\end_inset

, tag 4 transmits in the first slot alone.
 Thus, it is a successful slot.
 In the second slot, no tag has replied.
 So, it is an empty slot.
 In the third slot, tags 2 and 3 have replied together, which results in
 a collided slot.
 According to the FSA rules, tags 3 and 4 are not allowed to resubmit their
 IDs again during the same frame.
 Thus in slot 
\begin_inset Formula $4$
\end_inset

, only tag 
\begin_inset Formula $1$
\end_inset

 is allowed to reply to have another successful slot.
 In the next frame, the same procedure is repeated until all tags are identified.
 
\begin_inset Float figure
wide false
sideways false
status collapsed

\begin_layout Plain Layout
\align center
\begin_inset Graphics
	filename Frame_slotted_ALOHA.emf
	lyxscale 15
	width 65page%

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Plain Layout
\begin_inset Caption Standard

\begin_layout Plain Layout
Example for Frame Slotted ALOHA 
\begin_inset CommandInset label
LatexCommand label
name "fig:Example-for-frame"

\end_inset


\end_layout

\end_inset


\end_layout

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Subsubsection*
Dynamic Frame Slotted ALOHA (DFSA)
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
The final type of ALOHA anti-collision protocols is Dynamic Framed Slotted
 ALOHA (DFSA) 
\begin_inset CommandInset citation
LatexCommand cite
key "DFSA_shoute_Random"

\end_inset


\begin_inset CommandInset nomenclature
LatexCommand nomenclature
symbol "DFSA"
description "Dynamic Frame Slotted ALOHA"

\end_inset

.
 Using this algorithm, the number of slots per frame is variable as shown
 in figure 
\begin_inset CommandInset ref
LatexCommand ref
reference "fig:Slots-of-Dynamic"

\end_inset

.
 According to the previously published RFID work, DFSA 
\begin_inset CommandInset citation
LatexCommand cite
key "Letter_2012"

\end_inset

 is the most widely used anti-collision protocol for RFID systems owing
 to its simplicity and robustness.
 In DFSA, the reading process is divided into successive frames, in which
 each frame includes a specific number of slots.
 During the reading process, each active tag randomly assigns itself to
 one of the available slots in the frame.
\begin_inset Float figure
wide false
sideways false
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout
\align center
\begin_inset Graphics
	filename Dynamic_Frame_slotted_ALOHA_2.emf
	lyxscale 13
	width 50page%

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Plain Layout
\begin_inset Caption Standard

\begin_layout Plain Layout
Slots of Dynamic Frame Slotted ALOHA 
\begin_inset CommandInset label
LatexCommand label
name "fig:Slots-of-Dynamic"

\end_inset


\end_layout

\end_inset


\end_layout

\end_inset

 Therefore, each slot can take one of the following three variable states:
 1) Successful Slot: One tag only chooses this slot, is fully identified,
 and then is deactivated by the reader within the successive frames.
 2) Collided Slot: Multiple tags reply, resulting in a collision.
 The collided tags normally remain in their active state and retry their
 transmission in the next frame.
 3) Empty Slot: No tag responds and the slot remains unused.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Increasing the reading speed can directly be translated into the maximization
 of the number of successful slots in reference to the number of idle or
 collided slots.
 Based on the random access theory 
\begin_inset CommandInset citation
LatexCommand cite
key "Aloha4_Vogt"

\end_inset

, for a given number of 
\begin_inset Formula $n$
\end_inset

 tags, the expected number of empty 
\begin_inset Formula $E,$
\end_inset

 successful 
\begin_inset Formula $S,$
\end_inset

 and collided 
\begin_inset Formula $C$
\end_inset

 slots in each frame with a length of 
\begin_inset Formula $L$
\end_inset

 slots can be expressed by the following equations:
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{equation}
E=L\left(1-\frac{1}{L}\right)^{n},\,S=n\left(1-\frac{1}{L}\right)^{n-1},\,C=L-E-S\label{eq: number of slot definition}
\end{equation}

\end_inset

The conventional definition of the expected reading efficiency 
\begin_inset Formula $\eta_{conv}$
\end_inset

 is given by the ratio between the expected number of successful slots 
\begin_inset Formula $S$
\end_inset

 in a frame and the frame length 
\begin_inset Formula $L$
\end_inset

 
\begin_inset CommandInset citation
LatexCommand cite
key "L_equal_n"

\end_inset

:
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{equation}
\eta_{conv}=\frac{S}{L}\label{eq:eff basic equ}
\end{equation}

\end_inset

Based on (
\begin_inset CommandInset ref
LatexCommand ref
reference "eq: number of slot definition"

\end_inset

) and (
\begin_inset CommandInset ref
LatexCommand ref
reference "eq:eff basic equ"

\end_inset

), the conventional definition of the reading efficiency is:
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{equation}
\eta_{conv}=\frac{n}{L}\left(1-\frac{1}{L}\right)^{n-1}\label{eq:eff calss f(L)}
\end{equation}

\end_inset

Figure 
\begin_inset CommandInset ref
LatexCommand ref
reference "fig:Framed-Slotted-ALOHA"

\end_inset

 shows the FSA reading efficiency 
\begin_inset Formula $\eta_{conv}$
\end_inset

 for a constant frame length 
\begin_inset Formula $L=64$
\end_inset

 and different numbers of tags.
 The main goal of optimizing the DFSA algorithm is finding the optimal frame
 length 
\begin_inset Formula $L$
\end_inset

, which maximizes the reading efficiency 
\begin_inset Formula $\eta_{conv}$
\end_inset

.
 Based on (
\begin_inset CommandInset ref
LatexCommand ref
reference "eq:eff calss f(L)"

\end_inset

), the reading efficiency 
\begin_inset Formula $\eta_{conv}$
\end_inset

 is maximized when:
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{equation}
L_{opt}=n\label{eq:L=n}
\end{equation}

\end_inset

 In practical applications, the number of tags 
\begin_inset Formula $n$
\end_inset

 in the interrogation region is unknown.
 Furthermore, the number of tags may even vary, e\SpecialChar \@.
g\SpecialChar \@.
 when the tags are mounted
 on moving goods.
 Therefore, such applications employ DFSA 
\begin_inset CommandInset citation
LatexCommand cite
key "Vogt_1"

\end_inset

.
 First, DFSA has to estimate the number of tags in the interrogation area,
 then it calculates the optimal frame size 
\begin_inset Formula $L$
\end_inset

 for the next reading frame.
 Figure 
\begin_inset CommandInset ref
LatexCommand ref
reference "fig:Flow-chart-of"

\end_inset

 presents a summary for DFSA.
 As shown in the chart, the reader starts with an initial frame length.
 Then, it broadcasts this frame length to the tags in the reading area.
 Afterwards, it performs a normal FSA.
\begin_inset Float figure
wide false
sideways false
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout
\align center
\begin_inset Graphics
	filename reading_efficiency.emf
	lyxscale 50
	width 60page%
	height 25pheight%

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Plain Layout
\begin_inset Caption Standard

\begin_layout Plain Layout
Conventional FSA reading efficiency 
\begin_inset Formula $\eta_{conv}$
\end_inset

 as a function of the number of tags 
\begin_inset Formula $n$
\end_inset

, maximum reached for 
\begin_inset Formula $L=n=64$
\end_inset

 tags of 
\begin_inset Formula $\eta_{max}=(1/e)\simeq0.36$
\end_inset

 
\begin_inset CommandInset label
LatexCommand label
name "fig:Framed-Slotted-ALOHA"

\end_inset


\end_layout

\end_inset


\end_layout

\end_inset

 At the end of the frame, the reader checks if there are any successful
 or collided slots.
 If yes, the reader estimates the remaining number of tags in the reading
 area, then optimizes the next frame length and starts again normal FSA.
 If not, the reading cycle will be terminated.
