\begin_layout Standard
Figure 
\begin_inset CommandInset ref
LatexCommand ref
reference "fig:Single-tag-reply"

\end_inset

 shows the case of a single tag reply.
 In this case, the tag replies with its Random Number 16 (RN16)
\begin_inset CommandInset nomenclature
LatexCommand nomenclature
symbol "RN16"
description "Random Number 16"

\end_inset

, which is a 16 bits random number.
 When the reader receives this RN16 it will acknowledge this tag with an
 
\begin_inset Quotes eld
\end_inset

ACK
\begin_inset Quotes erd
\end_inset

 command including this RN16.
 As soon as the tag receives a valid Acknowledgment (ACK)
\begin_inset CommandInset nomenclature
LatexCommand nomenclature
symbol "ACK"
description "Acknowledgment"

\end_inset

 with its RN16, it will reply with its unique Electronic Product Code (EPC)
\begin_inset CommandInset nomenclature
LatexCommand nomenclature
symbol "EPC"
description "Electronic Product Code"

\end_inset

.
 Finally, the reader will send a 
\begin_inset Quotes eld
\end_inset

Handle
\begin_inset Quotes erd
\end_inset

 command to the tag to mute it until the end of the complete reading process.
 In figure 
\begin_inset CommandInset ref
LatexCommand ref
reference "fig:Multiple-tags-reply"

\end_inset

, the reader starts broadcasting a 
\begin_inset Quotes eld
\end_inset

Query
\begin_inset Quotes erd
\end_inset

 command for tags in the reading area.
 In the presented example, three tags select this slot.
 Therefore, the reader receives simultaneously three different RN16s.
 In this case, the conventional RFID reader will not be able to decode any
 of these RN16s.
 The tags will wait for the next frame to be identified.
 Afterwards, the reader broadcasts a 
\begin_inset Quotes eld
\end_inset

Query-rep
\begin_inset Quotes erd
\end_inset

 command to inform all the remaining tags that the next slot will start.
 Figure 
\begin_inset CommandInset ref
LatexCommand ref
reference "fig:No-tag-reply"

\end_inset

 shows the behavior of an empty slot in EPCglobal C1 G2.
 The reader starts with a 
\begin_inset Quotes eld
\end_inset

Query
\begin_inset Quotes erd
\end_inset

 command, and waits for a tag reply during a certain time out period.
 If there is no tag reply during this time, the reader will terminate the
 slot by sending a new 
\begin_inset Quotes eld
\end_inset

Query-rep
\begin_inset Quotes erd
\end_inset

 command.
 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Section
Cross Layer Anti-Collision Protocol
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Recently, RFID receivers have been developed, that are able to convert part
 of the collided slots into successful slots.
 Moreover, new RFID readers can even identify the type of the slots and
 terminate the empty and collided slots earlier.
 In this section, a brief discussion about these two parameters will be
 presented.
 Afterwards, a motivation to reconfigure the MAC layer to make use of the
 PHY-layer parameters is presented.
 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Subsection
Collision Recovery in UHF RFID
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Collision recovery in RFID systems is the capability of the reader to convert
 part of the collided slots into successful slots.
 According to EPCglobal C1 G2, the reader can only acknowledge one single
 tag per slot.
 According to 
\begin_inset CommandInset citation
LatexCommand cite
key "2013_capture"

\end_inset

, the collision recovery capability of the RFID system depends on different
 factors: First, the capabilities of the receiver, e.g.
 number of antennas.
 Second, the distance between the collided tags.
 Finally, the type of the channel.
 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Recently, some research groups (e.g.
 
\begin_inset CommandInset citation
LatexCommand cite
key "Capture_2011"

\end_inset

) have concentrated on collision recovery using the spatial diversity of
 the received signal.
 They have proposed the following reading efficiency equation:
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{equation}
\eta=P(1)+\alpha\cdot\sum_{i=2}^{n}P(i),\label{eq:eff_PHY_2}
\end{equation}

\end_inset

where 
\begin_inset Formula $\sum_{i=2}^{n}P(i)$
\end_inset

 is the probability of collision, and 
\begin_inset Formula $\alpha$
\end_inset

 is the average collision resolving probability.
 In this efficiency equation, the RFID reader can convert the collided slots
 into successful slots with a probability 
\begin_inset Formula $\alpha$
\end_inset

.
 The authors have assumed unlimited and equal collision resolving probability
 coefficients.
 For example, the probability to resolve two collided tags is identical
 to the probability to resolve ten collided tags, which is an unpractical
 assumption, because the more collided tags per slot, the lower collision
 recovery capability.
 Another research groups 
\begin_inset CommandInset citation
LatexCommand cite
key "2012_journal_CR,PHY111,PHY112,PHY113"

\end_inset

 considered the limited capability of a RFID reader to resolve collisions.
 They have proposed a limited reading efficiency expressed as:
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{equation}
\eta=\sum_{i=1}^{M}P(i),\label{eq:rff_PHY}
\end{equation}

\end_inset

where 
\begin_inset Formula $P(i)=\binom{n}{i}\left(\frac{1}{L}\right)^{i}\left(1-\frac{1}{L}\right)^{n-i}$
\end_inset

, and 
\begin_inset Formula $M$
\end_inset

 represents the number of collided tags that the reader is capable to recover.
 The authors assumed that the probability to recover one tag from 
\begin_inset Formula $i$
\end_inset

 collided tags equals to 
\begin_inset Formula $100\%$
\end_inset

, independently of the actual 
\begin_inset Formula $i$
\end_inset

.
 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
According to (
\begin_inset CommandInset ref
LatexCommand ref
reference "eq:eff_PHY_2"

\end_inset

) and (
\begin_inset CommandInset ref
LatexCommand ref
reference "eq:rff_PHY"

\end_inset

), the reading efficiency strongly depends on the capability of the PHY
 layer to resolve the collision.
 Thus, in this thesis, the effect of the collision recovery capability on
 the MAC layer optimization will be addressed in more details.
\begin_inset Float figure
wide false
sideways false
status collapsed

\begin_layout Plain Layout
\noindent
\align center
\begin_inset Graphics
	filename Total_slots.emf
	lyxscale 20
	width 65page%

\end_inset


\end_layout

