\begin_layout Subsection
Slots Durations in EPCglobal C1 G2
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Conventional RFID systems cannot identify the type of the slots in FSA 
\begin_inset CommandInset citation
LatexCommand cite
key "Vogt_1"

\end_inset

.
 Therefore, such systems consider that the slot duration of FSA is constant,
 neglecting the type of the slot.
 However, modern RFID readers can quickly identify the type of a slot (i\SpecialChar \@.
e\SpecialChar \@.

 idle, successful, or collided).
 Hence, the durations of the different slot types are not identical, which
 normally reduces the overall reading time.
 Figure 
\begin_inset CommandInset ref
LatexCommand ref
reference "fig:Differences-between-the-1"

\end_inset

 shows two frames, each one with a frame length of 
\begin_inset Formula $L=6$
\end_inset

 slots.
 The first frame in (a) presents the conventional view of the frame with
 equal slots durations 
\begin_inset Formula $t_{Slot}$
\end_inset

 for all slot types.
 The second frame in (b) presents the behavior of the real RFID slots behavior.
 Here, the slot duration depends on the slot type.
 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Figure 
\begin_inset CommandInset ref
LatexCommand ref
reference "fig:Measured-Slots-durations-1"

\end_inset

 shows an example of real measurements for slots durations using the Universal
 Software Radio Peripheral SDR receiver (USRP B210) 
\begin_inset CommandInset citation
LatexCommand cite
key "USRP"

\end_inset

.
 In these measurements, the tag data rate is 
\begin_inset Formula $\unit[160]{kbps}$
\end_inset

 and a sampling frequency of 
\begin_inset Formula $f_{s}=\unit[8]{MHz}$
\end_inset

 is used, because the total RFID bandwidth in the European system is 
\begin_inset Formula $\unit[4]{MHz}$
\end_inset

.
 For the given parameters and as shown in figure 
\begin_inset CommandInset ref
LatexCommand ref
reference "fig:Measured-Slots-durations-1"

\end_inset

, the collided slot duration is 
\begin_inset Formula $\simeq\unit[1200]{\mu sec}$
\end_inset

, and the empty slot duration is 
\begin_inset Formula $\simeq\unit[200]{\mu sec}$
\end_inset

.
 Figure 
\begin_inset CommandInset ref
LatexCommand ref
reference "fig:Collided-Slot-Duration-1"

\end_inset

 shows a real collided slot between two tags.
 The number of Amplitude Shift Keying (ASK) levels in the RN16 is 
\begin_inset Formula $A_{L}=2^{N_{c}}$
\end_inset

, where 
\begin_inset Formula $N_{c}$
\end_inset

 is the number of collided tags.
 As shown in figure 
\begin_inset CommandInset ref
LatexCommand ref
reference "fig:Collided-Slot-Duration-1"

\end_inset

, the number of ASK levels 
\begin_inset Formula $A_{L}=4$
\end_inset

.
 In such a slot, the reader terminates the slot after recognizing that the
 slot is a collided slot.
 Figure 
\begin_inset CommandInset ref
LatexCommand ref
reference "fig:Empty-Slot-Duration-1"

\end_inset

 shows that the reader terminates the slot directly when it recognizes that
 there is no tag reply in this slot.
 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
According to the above discussion, the reading efficiency equation will
 be affected by the different slots durations.
 In this thesis, the different slot duration lengths will be addressed in
 more details in the MAC layer optimization.
 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Summarizing, the main lack in the previous RFID research is that the MAC
 layer is optimized independently on the PHY layer.
 However, the PHY-layer properties affect the optimization parameters of
 the MAC layer, e.g.
 the number of tags estimation and the optimum frame length.
 This thesis concentrates on optimizing the DFSA anti-collision protocol.
 In the proposed algorithm, the PHY layer parameters will be considered,
 which are the collision recovery capability of the RFID reader and the
 differences in slot durations.
\end_layout

